"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>更多食品和饮料</h4><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blue-crab-recipe-this-3-ingredient-feast-is-a-summer-weekend-showstopper-6f58784d?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">螃蟹、玉米、黄油：这三种食材的盛宴是夏季周末的亮点</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cocktail-ratios-for-easy-drinks-at-home-4b4b9c36?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">记住这些鸡尾酒比例，以便在家轻松饮用</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crab-risotto-recipe-worthy-of-sophia-loren-bb330842?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这道快捷蟹肉烩饭是值得索菲亚·罗兰 (Sophia Loren) 的夏日食谱</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grilled-calamari-recipe-e7196b17?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在烧烤车辙中？这道海鲜快餐就是答案</a></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-healthy-vietnamese-recipes-this-gen-x-chef-consulted-a-master-mom-39d9d919?mod=article_relatedinline&amp;mod=article_relatedinline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对于健康的越南食谱，这位 X 世代厨师咨询了一位大师：妈妈</a></li></ul></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-glass-of-wine-a-day-64ead6a9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/one-glass-of-wine-a-day-64ead6a9<author><![CDATA[Lettie Teague]]></author><category> off duty</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>食物和饮料</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>食物</category><category>喝</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Economic Growth Accelerates]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Economy grew 2.4% last quarter, suggesting the US is steering clear of recession <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="581" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824191?width=860&amp;height=581" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">消费者支出一直在推动美国经济。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贾斯汀·沙利文/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087898"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sarah-chaney-cambon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sarah Chaney Cambon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 8:49（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-economy-consumer-spending-92482437"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管美联储<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-reserve-raises-interest-rates-to-22-year-high-3c3e499c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">提高了利率，</a>美国经济上个季度依然强劲增长，并且远离衰退。</p><p>美国商务部周四表示，第二季度<a href="https://www.bea.gov/data/gdp/gross-domestic-product" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">国内生产总值(GDP)</a>季节性和通胀调整后年增长率为2.4%，略高于今年前三个月2%的增长率。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-economy-retail-sales-may-2023-c9ddefcb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">今年春季消费者支出有所增长</a>，但商品和服务支出增速均放缓。 4 月至 6 月，商业投资有所加强，企业在建筑和设备上的支出强劲。</p><p>总体而言，GDP 报告进一步证明经济在利率上升的情况下仍保持弹性。劳动力市场依然紧张，通胀正在缓解。</p><p>在许多人预计<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/economists-are-cutting-back-their-recession-expectations-74118938?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经济衰退将在今年年中开始以应对美联储政策后，经济学家现在正在下调经济</a>衰退预期。美联储周三采取行动，将基准利率提高至 22 年来的高点。主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔不排除再次加息的可能性，但强调加息可能需要一段时间才能冷却通胀。</p><p> AC Cutts &amp; Associates 首席经济学家艾米·克鲁斯·卡茨 (Amy Crews Cutts) 在数据发布前表示：“我们已经扭转了这里的风险，不再过度关注衰退，而是在衰退与非衰退之间保持平衡。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="850" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824776?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3>消费者支出推动经济发展</h3><p>消费者正在增加在旅行和大件商品等体验方面的支出。美国人正受益于强劲的劳动力市场，工资涨幅最近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pay-raises-are-finally-beating-inflation-after-two-years-of-falling-behind-3e89bc2d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">超过了降温的通胀。</a></p><p>今年年初，随着供应链中断的缓解，消费者在回流经销商停车场时抢购车辆。他们还在网上和餐馆消费更多。</p><p>尚不清楚今年晚些时候消费者是否会以同样的速度消费。高利率将持续存在，使得美国人经常贷款购买的汽车、电器和其他产品变得更加昂贵。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/student-loan-debt-repayment-money-budget-7d81f540?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">学生贷款偿还</a>将于今年晚些时候恢复。美国人正在耗尽他们在疫情爆发初期在家积累的积蓄。</p><p>德意志银行证券公司高级美国经济学家布雷特·瑞安表示：“有很多煤矿里的金丝雀迹象表明消费者支出将会放缓。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6B575582-5695-4577-8048-E886C31EFE0B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fus-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔周三表示，央行将把基准利率提高四分之一个百分点，使美国利率升至22年来的最高点。照片：内森·霍华德/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>投资数据显示利率的影响</h3><p>公司在年初放缓了投资，削减了设备采购。</p><p>住宅投资下降。商业和住宅投资对利率都高度敏感。</p><p>一些长期力量也在塑造投资趋势。例如，联邦政府在芯片制造厂和电动汽车工厂方面的支出激增，抵消了一些私营部门的削减开支。</p><p>尽管抵押贷款利率上升，但二手房的长期短缺正在帮助支持新建筑。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/housings-recession-already-happened-26bbb505?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">房地产市场低迷</a>最严重的时期可能已经成为过去。随着更多的建设正在进行，未来几个月住宅投资可能会增长。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1300" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824784?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3> More upbeat outlook</h3><p>消费者、企业和经济学家对前景感到更加乐观。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1" target="_blank" class="icon none">通胀从历史高位回落</a>且劳动力市场依然吃紧， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-inflation-goes-down-soft-landing-odds-improve-5166e6af" target="_blank" class="icon none">软着陆</a>的前景——即通胀在不出现衰退的情况下回归到接近<a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/news-explainers/the-feds-2-inflation-target-explained/F0A8BD11-B153-4E7E-8454-B5C1C8CD12BD?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美联储 2% 的目标</a>——的可能性似乎更大。</p><p>世界大型企业联合会本周表示，7 月份美国消费者信心继续改善，许多美国人对未来表示更加乐观。消费者对经济衰退的担忧减少。</p><p>小企业对经济的悲观情绪有所缓解。商业辅导和同行咨询公司伟事达 (Vistage Worldwide) 的数据显示，7 月，37% 的小企业表示，他们认为未来 12 个月经济将恶化，这是自 2022 年 2 月以来的最佳记录。</p><p>国际货币基金组织周二表示，今年美国和全球的经济增长可能会强于此前的估计。前景的改善反映了劳动力市场的强劲、旅游业等服务业支出的强劲以及金融稳定风险的降低。</p><p>写信给 Sarah Chaney Cambon，邮箱为<a href="mailto:sarah.chaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sarah.chaney@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/b53b02aa-8e94-4e61-9c59-71310c5dc08d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 12:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-gdp-report-economic-growth-92482437<author><![CDATA[Sarah Chaney Cambon]]></author><category>通货膨胀</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>银行业</category><category>Central Banking</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>Consumer Spending/Budgeting</category><category>通货膨胀</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>货币政策</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>个人财务</category><category>consumer spending</category><category> budgeting</category><category>银行业</category><category>central banking</category><category> credit</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The First Smart Gun Is Finally Coming to Market. Will Anyone Buy It?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Gun makers have been working for decades on a weapon that can only be fired by an authorized user <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822895/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Biofire’s Smart Gun will be the first of its kind to be widely available if it ships in December as planned." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Biofire&#39;s Smart Gun will be the first of its kind to be widely available if it ships in December as planned. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087021"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087021"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/zusha-elinson" itemprop="url" rel="author">Zusha Elinson</a></span> |丹尼尔·布伦纳 (Daniel Brenner) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 27 日上午 8:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-first-smart-gun-is-finally-coming-to-market-will-anyone-buy-it-67314e0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>萨沙·维森 (Sasha Wiesen) 睡觉时床边的保险箱里放着一把 0.40 口径的手枪。这位来自佛罗里达州的商业房地产经纪人最近预订了一种新型枪支，他希望能让保险箱变得不再必要。</p><p>这款新武器是科罗拉多州初创公司 Biofire 的 9 毫米智能枪，只有当它通过手柄上的指纹识别器或背面的面部识别摄像头识别授权用户时才能发射。</p><p> “我通常是早期适应者，”46 岁的 Wiesen 说。 “可能是我的小玩意让我买了它，但也是出于安全方面的考虑。”</p><p>自 20 世纪 90 年代以来，人们一直在开发和争论使用技术来确保只能由其所有者开枪的枪支（称为智能枪）。如果 Biofire 智能枪按计划于 12 月发货，它将成为第一款广泛销售的智能枪。</p><p>支持者宣称智能枪支是减少意外枪击和枪支盗窃的一种方式。枪支权利支持者一直保持警惕，部分原因是担心政府可能禁止销售不具备智能枪支技术的武器。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7e082dbe-e1c8-4a09-a3b8-9a8a34131654.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>早期将智能枪支推向市场的努力失败了，主要是因为枪支权利活动人士的压力，或者是因为它们没有按照承诺发挥作用。</p><p>与改变历史悠久的产品的电动汽车等其他技术一样，智能枪的问题是它们是否至少能像它们所取代的传统版本一样工作，并在富裕的早期采用者背后找到客户。</p><p> Biofire 智能枪售价 1,499 美元。没有高科技功能的类似手枪通常售价在 400 至 800 美元之间。</p><p>当地枪支权利组织圣地亚哥县枪支所有者执行董事迈克尔·施瓦茨表示，许多枪支拥有者仍然对具有高科技功能的枪支持怀疑态度。</p><p> “对于我们大多数会员来说，拥有枪支的主要目的是自卫，所以越简单越好，”他说。 “它必须 110% 可靠。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822885?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Biofire 创始人 Kai Kloepfer 表示，已有数千人预订了这款智能枪，可在线购买。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Biofire 创始人 Kai Kloepfer，26 岁，从青少年时期就开始研究这项技术。他说，他已经建立了指纹和面部识别系统，这样，如果一个功能因为一个人的手湿了或者看不到这个人的脸而无法工作，另一个功能就会起作用。</p><p> Biofire 成立于 2014 年，已筹集了 3000 万美元资金，资金来源包括风险投资家 Ron Conway（自 2012 年桑迪胡克小学枪击事件以来一直在推广智能枪技术）和 Peter Thiel 的创始人基金。康涅狄格州纽敦发生校园枪击事件，造成 20 名儿童和 6 名成人死亡。</p><p>克洛普弗表示，已有数千人预订了这款智能枪，该枪仅在网上销售，但他拒绝透露具体数字。</p><p>在今年早些时候的一次媒体演示中，生物火枪出现故障。克洛普弗表示，武器卡壳了，但指纹或面部识别系统没有出现问题。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1200" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/6f986e60-4952-4982-bb7d-ed88c7c510ef-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>克洛普弗表示，他不喜欢智能枪强制令，一些枪支管制支持者推动这一强制令以刺激销售。与此类努力合作可能会疏远支持枪支权利的潜在 Biofire 客户。</p><p>新泽西州有一项法律，要求所有商店在智能枪上市后必须提供销售，但遭到了第二修正案团体的反对。克洛普弗表示，他不会将生物火智能枪提交给该州的个性化手枪授权委员会，该委员会将使该法律生效。</p><p> “我们对智能枪支采取了非常强烈的反强制立场，”他说。 “我坚信，这必须是一个选择。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822880?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Biofire&#39;s Smart Gun can only be fired if it recognizes an authorized user with a fingerprint reader on the grip or facial-recognition camera on the back.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>枪械制造商柯尔特 (Colt) 是 20 世纪 90 年代最早开发智能枪的公司之一。 Colt Z-40 的设计只有在射手佩戴发射编码无线电信号的手镯时才会开火。但它在《华尔街日报》的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB926462954670753455?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">演示中</a>并没有发挥作用，枪支拥有者抵制了该公司开发它的决定。 Z-40 从未上市。</p><p>德国公司Armatix在2010年代开发了一款0.22口径的智能手枪，使用了主人佩戴的射频识别手表。但在受到枪支权利活动人士的威胁后，枪支商店在 2014 年放弃了销售这些枪支的计划。</p><p>除了指出智能枪盗窃毫无意义之外，这些武器的倡导者还认为，它们可以防止儿童意外射击父母的枪支，或防止青少年在校园枪击或自杀中使用它们。枪支暴力研究人员 2003 年的一项研究发现，37% 的意外枪击事件本可以通过此类技术来避免。</p><p>约翰霍普金斯大学彭博公共卫生学院 2019 年的一项研究发现，已经安全存放枪支的枪支拥有者购买智能枪支的可能性高出 50%，这表明其影响可能有限。研究还发现，虽然大约十分之八的枪支拥有者支持销售智能枪支，但十分之二的人可能会购买一把。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822886?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Biofire 的一名工程师走进这家智能枪制造商位于科罗拉多州的射击场。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>其他初创公司也在研发智能枪，但没有一家公司计划像 Biofire 一样立即开始销售他们的产品。总部位于堪萨斯州的自由州枪械公司总裁汤姆·霍兰德表示，他的公司正在使用用户佩戴的射频识别环。</p><p> “当人们听说指纹扫描时，就像是，‘哦，天啊，我有一半时间无法打开我的手机，’”霍兰德谈到 Biofire 使用的技术时说道。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为大众市场智能枪支的出现将如何改变有关枪支管制的讨论？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>霍兰德表示，自由州计划明年初推出该枪。他说，该武器正在接受六家警察机构的测试，并且他已经收到了一些消费者的预订单。</p><p>曾在执法部门工作的维森表示，他对 Biofire 智能枪的可定制美观以及其安全功能很感兴趣。他订购的是全白的。</p><p> “当你在靶场开枪时，会发生一些很酷的事情，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Zusha Elinson： <a href="mailto:zusha.elinson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">zusha.elinson@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-first-smart-gun-is-finally-coming-to-market-will-anyone-buy-it-67314e0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-first-smart-gun-is-finally-coming-to-market-will-anyone-buy-it-67314e0<author><![CDATA[Zusha Elinson]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> guns</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Gun Control</category><category> Rampage/Serial Killings</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>社会问题</category><category>Guns</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>gun control</category><category> rampage</category><category> serial killings</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[An Unwelcome Visitor Returns This Summer. Hint: It’s Covid.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Hearing about a smattering of Covid cases again? There&#39;s a reason <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824544/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Margeaux Walter for The Wall Street Journal <span>Margeaux Walter for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087824"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087824"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sumathi-reddy" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sumathi Reddy</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 27, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Summer is bringing us hot days, vacations—and a Covid bump.</p><p> If you are surprised to learn that your neighbor, co-worker or kid&#39;s best friend just tested positive for Covid-19, don&#39;t be. Measures of Covid rates including virus levels in wastewater, ER visits, test positivity and hospital admissions are increasing nationally, according to the most recent Centers for Disease Control and Prevention <a href="https://covid.cdc.gov/covid-data-tracker/?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_medium=email#maps_new-admissions-rate-county" target="_blank" class="icon none">data</a> . The good news is that we are starting from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-covid-19-deaths-and-hospitalizations-near-new-lows-9151bc18?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">very low rates</a> .</p><p> Doctors are watching the current trends for clues to Covid&#39;s yearly pattern going forward. Other <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-does-flu-spread-compared-with-covid-what-to-know-as-flu-cases-surge-11667882271?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">respiratory viruses such as flu</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-approves-first-rsv-drug-to-protect-all-infants-from-virus-52907caf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">RSV</a> typically start spreading in the fall and peak in the winter. Covid, a much newer virus that has mutated a lot since emerging a few years ago, so far has had winter surges as well as summer bumps, like we&#39;re seeing again this year.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> One possible factor: <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sun-tired-hot-weather-heat-bb750670?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Heat waves</a> are sending people fleeing for air-conditioned indoor spaces, where Covid transmits more easily compared with outside. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/airport-travel-tips-flight-summer-a6771549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Summer travel</a> might also play a role, as people crowd into airports and bring their germs along with them crisscrossing the world.</p><p> “We are in a very warm year and people are spending a lot of time indoors,” said Dr. Luis Ostrosky, chief of infectious diseases <strong>&nbsp;</strong> and epidemiology at UTHealth Houston and Memorial Hermann-Texas Medical Center. “People are congregating in air-conditioned settings and that is providing an opportunity for transmission.”</p><p> Covid-19 hospitalizations as of July 15 are up 10.3% from the previous week, according to CDC data. Emergency department visits are up 7% and test positivity rose to 6.3% from 5.8%. Hospital admissions include both people hospitalized for Covid as well as those who test positive when they come in to be treated for something else. Deaths remain low.</p><p> Overall, Covid rates are still near historic lows, a CDC spokeswoman noted. And for most people, Covid is far less dangerous than it once was.</p><p> “Because we may start seeing seasonality patterns like we do with other respiratory diseases, I think how big this wave gets this summer will be very telling,” says Katelyn Jetelina, a scientific adviser to the CDC and White House and author of the “Your Local Epidemiologist” newsletter.</p><p> There is no new Covid strain behind current cases. A mix of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-target-xbb-strain-when-covid-shots-roll-out-this-fall-178702e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">XBB variants</a> , which are offshoots of Omicron, play the largest role, say scientists and doctors.</p><p> Covid mutates faster than influenza, so it&#39;s changing more quickly and able to better evade people&#39;s immunity from prior infections, says Jetelina.</p><p> Covid-tracking data isn&#39;t as comprehensive as it once was. Many people aren&#39;t testing at all, and use <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-i-trust-my-rapid-covid-19-test-if-it-says-im-negative-11654650057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">home rapid tests</a> if they do, which typically don&#39;t get reported to health authorities.</p><p> Since the federal government formally <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-public-health-emergency-is-over-92ee814d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">declared the end of the pandemic</a> as a public health emergency in May, labs no longer are required to submit data on Covid-19 testing. Instead, the CDC testing positivity data comes from more than 400 labs that voluntarily submit data. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824302?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Virus levels in wastewater have ticked up in the Northeast, according to one company&#39;s data.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Matias Basualdo/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Wastewater testing provides some regional clues. In Houston, wastewater measures have tripled over the past three weeks, says Ostrosky at UTHealth Houston and Memorial Hermann. “That&#39;s always a precursor to what we&#39;re going to be seeing clinically,” he notes.</p><p> Already, the hospital and clinic have seen roughly double the number of people testing positive for Covid-19 over the past two to three weeks, Ostrosky says.</p><p> Mariana Matus, CEO and co-founder of Biobot, a Cambridge, Mass., wastewater epidemiology company, says their data shows an 8% increase compared with the prior week in the level of the virus that causes Covid nationally. “It&#39;s been this consistent uptick over the past several weeks,” says Matus.</p><p> In the Northeast, levels were 26% higher for the week ending July 19 compared with the previous week. Levels were 9% higher in the South, she says.</p><p> Overall, wastewater virus levels are still low, says Matus. Wastewater concentrations were four times higher last summer than currently and in recent days the numbers have started to decrease, which means the wave might already be peaking.</p><p> Caitlin Rivers, an epidemiologist at the Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security, says Covid trend rates don&#39;t necessarily warrant changing behaviors if you&#39;re young and healthy. But elderly people and those who are immunocompromised might want to keep a closer eye on the numbers and act more cautiously, including masking in crowded indoor spaces, if they continue to rise for another month.</p><p> “It&#39;s not like we are deep in a wave,” says Rivers. “It&#39;s just heading in a direction that&#39;s making us pay closer attention.”</p><p> Write to Sumathi Reddy at <a href="mailto:Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Sumathi.Reddy@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 27 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/covid-19-rates-rising-summer-780ab1d7<author><![CDATA[Sumathi Reddy]]></author><category>摄影委托</category><category>WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>health</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category></item></channel></rss>